BUBBLE SORT IS ONE OF THE SIMPLEST SORTING ALGO








HOW IT WORKS
campares the first and second elements
if the first is greater than the second, swap them
move to the next pair and repeat until the end of the array
repeat the entire process n-1 times

Input Array:
[5, 8, 7, 5, 6, 4, 2, 56, 6, 9, 20]

Pass 1: Finding the Largest
- Compare [5, 8] → 5 < 8 → No swap
- Compare [8, 7] → 8 > 7 → Swap → [5, 7, 8, 5, 6, 4, 2, 56, 6, 9, 20]
- Compare [8, 5] → 8 > 5 → Swap → [5, 7, 5, 8, 6, 4, 2, 56, 6, 9, 20]
- Compare [8, 6] → 8 > 6 → Swap → [5, 7, 5, 6, 8, 4, 2, 56, 6, 9, 20]
- Continue until 8 meets 56
- Compare [8, 56] → 8 < 56 → No swap
- Compare [56, 6] → 56 > 6 → Swap
- Compare [56, 9] → 56 > 9 → Swap
- Compare [56, 20] → 56 > 20 → Swap

End of Pass 1:
[5, 7, 5, 6, 4, 2, 8, 6, 9, 20, 56]
Result: Largest element (56) has bubbled to the end and is locked.

Pass 2: Finding the 2nd Largest
- Compare [5, 7] → No swap
- Compare [7, 5] → Swap → [5, 5, 7, 6, 4, 2, 8, 6, 9, 20, 56]
- Compare [7, 6] → Swap → [5, 5, 6, 7, 4, 2, 8, 6, 9, 20, 56]
- 7 continues swapping with smaller numbers
- Compare [7, 8] → 7 < 8 → No swap
- Compare [8, 6] → Swap
- Compare [8, 9] → No swap
- Compare [9, 20] → No swap

End of Pass 2:
[5, 5, 6, 4, 2, 7, 6, 8, 9, 20, 56]
Result: Second largest element (20) is locked at the second-to-last position.

Summary of Bubbling:
- Pass 1: [..., 20, 56]
- Pass 2: [..., 9, 20, 56]
- Pass 3: [..., 8, 9, 20, 56]
- Pass 4: [..., 7, 8, 9, 20, 56]
- Pass 5: [..., 6, 7, 8, 9, 20, 56]














Case,Time Complexity,When does this happen?
Best     Case,O(N),Array is already sorted (Optimized version only).
Average  Case,O(N2),Array is in random order.
Worst    Case,O(N2),Array is sorted in reverse order.
Space Complexity,O(1),"No extra space needed; it sorts ""in-place."""













Stable? Yes (it preserves the relative order of equal elements).
In-place? Yes (it doesn't need extra memory).
Use Case? Education purposes or extremely small datasets.
